{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580382/1945083101/1006.xml":{"full_text":"Friday, August 31, 1945\nMurray Reviews Scene\nBy Philip Murray, President Congress of Industrial Organization\nOn Labor Day, 1945, labor shares the pride of all Amer\nicans in the magnificent record of our armed forces, as\nSignalized by the complete defeat of the Japanese and Nazis.\nLabor has contributed mightily to these successes.\nIn the sphere of international relations, labor has also\n9 done its part for the continu\ning unity of the United Na\n*is. The San Francisco\nCharter has laid a firm founda\ntion for world organization\nagainst fascism, .aggression and\nfuture war, while the World\nConference of Trade Unions has\nmade splendid progress in unit\ning the working people of all\nCountries, for these and other\n1 common purposes.\nBut on the domestic scene,\nunfortunately, American labor\nfinds fewer grounds for satis\nfaction.\nIn its unparalleled\" war\nachievements, America has\nshown a capacity, for organiza\ntion and production that should\nassure the full employment of\nour people after the war in cre\nwing unparalleled prosperity for\n\"1. But, with reconversion al\nready under way, there are\nmany tragic signs that selfish\nprivilege and governmental in\nertia are obstructing the fulfill\nment of this promise.\nPurchasing Power Slashed\nThe mass purchasing power\nof American working people\nmust obviously be one of the\nmain pillars of our postwar\nprosperity. Yet today this pur\nchasing power is being cruelly\nslashed by layoffs, loss of over\ntime, downgrading and gene\nrally reduced take-home- pay,\nWhile the infamous incubus of\nthe Little Steel formula smoth\ners collective bargaining and\nholds wages far below sky-high\nliving costs.\nCongress meanwhile has been\nFflger and quick to provide\nJfeofit guarantees and other pro\nlions for business in recon\nversion, but has not lifted a fin\nger to aid the worst victims of\nreconversion, the laid-off war\nWorkers.\nThere is also a lamentable\nlack of national planning for\nfull employment, and a ten\ndency to lift production and\nprice controls in such a way as\nto restore The \u201cnormalcy\u201d of un\nlimited grabbing for the few and\ndepression and unemployment\nfor the many.\nCalls For Reversal\nOn this Labor Day, the CIO\ncalls upon our political and in\ndustrial leaders to join with la\nbor and the whole American\npeople in re-- dis\nastrous tre- too\n^|ate.\nWe urge the immediate revi\nsion of our national wage policy\nto end the Little Steel Freeze}\nto permit substantial wage ad\njustments, and to eliminate sub\nstandard wages below 65c ap\nhour.\nWe urge Congress, immediate\u00ad\nryaw\nly it reconvenes, to adopt Presi\ndent Truman's emergency pro\nposals for $25 a week for 26\nweeks for unemployed war\nworkers, as embodied in the\nKilgore-Forand bill.\nWe urge the speedy adoption\nof the guaranteed annual wage\nin collective bargaining agree\nments throughout industry.\nUrges Security Expansion\nSo the American people may\nhave freedom from fear and\nwant, we urge expansion of our\nsocial security system, as pro\nposed in the Murray-Wagner2\nDingell bill. And to end un\nAmerican discriminations,-. jve\ncall for a permanent Fair \u00a3n\nployment Practice Commission.\nWe also urge an immediate\nstart on over-all planning fdr\nfull production and jobs' for all,\nfor which a first step is passage\nof the Murray-Patman Eull.(\u00a3in\nployment bill\nAt the same time, we warn\nagainst the national uivujmn\nthreatened by plans for anti-un\nion drives and by such anti-la\nbor measures as the Ball-Bur\nton-Hatch bill, and call instead\nfor national unity and c\u2019ev\ntion in promoting national pros\nperity.\nIn the 'difficult days ahead,\nAmerican labor must above all\nbuild its union strength and in\ncrease its political activity, so\nthat it may make its full con\ntribution to complete victory\nover all anti-democratic forces\nand to a free and prosperous\npostwar America.\nFor the achievement of these\ngoals, the CIO offers its closest\ncooperation to all other AmerL\ncans who love their country ana\nseek its welfare.\nStudent Aid Urged\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\nTre nation should act now to\nfind ways of giving public aid\nto students 'who wish larger\neducational opportunities than\nare now open to them, says the\nNational Commission on Chil\ndren in Wartime. In a discussion\nof the problems of school age\nboys and girls, the Commission\nrecommends that the experience\nbeing gained in the administra\ntion of educational benefits un\nder the GI Bill of Rights should\nthrow +ight on how a program\nof student aid might be run. A\nfederal system of financial as\nsistance or scholarships might\nenable students to continue\nhigh school, or take advanced\nwork in vocational and agricul\ntural schools, technical institu\ntions, college and professional\nschools.\nA TRIRL\u2019Tl/\nTO LABOR\nand lloyx\nLabor Day, finds us on the road\nto peace. May tl(e men and women of indus\u00ad\ntry work as untiringly for enduring harmony\n\u00bbas they have^to produce ^he materials which\nplayed such an important part in overpower\ning the enemies of freedom,\nThe it II ItAKI-K\nAdams at Superior\nGLASS BAR\nWhJiin^Success To UAW-CIO\nOn Their 10th Anniversary\n(Jimmy Yes, Prop.)\nFormerly of Local 13...........\nCor. Phillips and Detroit\nWorkers\nStorm USES\nOffices\nWASHINGTON, Aug 27\n(LPA)\u2014Job offices all over the\ncountry were stormed by work\ners laid off by war contract\ncancellations last week, and\nlooking for peacetime work.\nAt the same time, official\nWashingtonians were picking\nthemselves up from the spots\nwhere they were blown by the\nblitz of the sudden Japanese\nsurrender.\nUnion leaders in communities\nwere almost the only people\ncoming to the fore with positive\nsuggestions for immediate ac\ntion to meet the crisis caused by\nthe war's end. In mass meet\nings, city-wide conferences of\nunionists, government and busi\nness officials, they were urging\nlabor\u2019s program of full produc\ntion, at high wages. Quick re\nconversion of individual plants\nto lessen interim unemploy\nment was also urged by union*\nists. In addition, of course,\nthey were backing up labor\u2019s\nnrogram for Congressional ac\ntion.\nNAM Is Calm\nThe only people who refused\nto recognize the gravity of the\nsituation were the spokesmen\nfor the National Association of\nManufacturers and the Com\nmittee for Economic Develop\nment. Both groups, made up of\nemployers, issued statements\ncomposed on what the NAM\nNews called \u201ca calm and re\nassuring note.\u201d The NAM\nlaughed down government and\nlabor estimates that unemploy\nment would run as high as 9\nor 10,000,000 by Christmas.\nMeanwhile, the War Mart\npower Commission is compiling\nthe first in what it expects will\nbe a series of reports, collected\nfrom every part of the nation\nby telegram, giving information\non numbers of unemployed.\nFragmentary reports, mainly,\nfrom the large cities, indicate\nthat labor\u2019s predictions are very\nclose to hitting the mark.\nThe Associated Press, in a\nquick check less than a week\nafter V-J day, estimated that\nat least 1,000,000 workers were\nfired because of contract termi\nnations. The Office of War\nMobilization and Reconversion\nhad predicted that only 1,100,\n000, would be out of work at\nthe end of the first month after\nV-J day, and most observers\nagree that the AP figure shows\nthe government agency as over\noptimistic.\nAFL Predicts Peak\n\u201cAFL\n'The publication, Labor\u2019s\nMonthly Survey, expects 3.800,\nOOO jobless by mid-September,\nand a peak of 8,000,000 unem\nployed in March, 1946.\nDetroit, where all concede\nthere ^re more than 250,000\njobless, is the hardest hit city\nin the country. Coming in a\nclose second is Los Angeles,\nalso affected by aircraft cut\nbacks, but expected to recover\nmuch more slowly because its\npeacetime aircraft industry will\nnot take up the jobless workers.\nShipyards in Pennsylvania.\nN. J., Massachusetts,. Maine,\nOregon, California, Maryland.\nGeorgia, Florida and Texas all\nare feeling the effects of the\nNavy cutback, and the cancel\nlation of $425,000,000 in con\ntracts for the construction of\nmerchant ships In Philadelphia,\nthousands of layoff slips were\nhanded out to workers return\ning from the surrender day\nholiday.\nThe 150,000 workers at the\nWright and Curtis-Wright\nplants across the country were\nsent home, and at best only\nabout half will be taken on for\npeacetime work. Most aircraft\nplants expect to take back\nabout that proportion of their\nwartime workers. GM will shut\ndown entirely its Eastern Air\ncraft division. General Electric\nexpects when reconversion is\ncomplete to have 135.000 work\ners contrasted with 155,000 at\nthe height of the war.\nCdifA0\"\"\"\n1\nPursm\nstep\nCom\nr\u00bbiN*\nTHE TOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nGrowing Up\nEmotionally\nBy Ruth Taylor\nThe one point upon which\nalmost all of those who discuss\nthe postwar world are in ac\ni cord is that it will be defi*\nnitely different than the world\nwe knew before the war. They\nare agreed that we are in one\nof the great transition period#\nof world history.\nTo face the problems of the\nnew day will require clear\nthinking and calm judgment,\nself-control and mental poise.\nWe must meet this challenge\nemotionally mature. No longer\ncan we indulge in the imma\nturity of adolescence. We are\nnot a nation of children. We\nare a nation\nyears.\nyoung only in\na nation is a\ntime, we have\nIn what to\nsmall span of\naccomplished much. We have\nproven beyond a doubt the\nworth 'of that brotherhood\nwhich is democracy. We have\nstruggled through .the serious\nillnesses of the early years of\nour Republic to form a union\nof states. We have even con\nquered the near death of a\nCivil War, to prove that all\nmen must be free.\nPractical Youth\nWe have more than ptflled\nthrough. We have shown\nclearly that the ideas of our\nyouth were practical, that our\nyouthful dreams of a world in,\nwhich all men were free,\nCOULD be fulfilled. We have\ndemonstrated that our way of\nlife could give (and what is\nmore to the point, has given)\nto all classes, all creeds, all\nconditions of people a better\nopportunity to develop to the\nfull stature of a free man than\nany other form of govern\nment.\nThis we have done with the\nImpetuousness though often\nwith the clumsy stumbling\u2014\nof youth. Revolution, change,\nshort cuts are the expression\nof the impatience of youth. A\nstable and enduring peace,\nhowever, requires reasoned\nand seasoned judgment to\nmaintain it. We must grow\nemotionally to show that we\nare capable of taking our\nplace at the council of free na\ntions, of playing a leading role\n\u2014not by force but by virtue\nof calm, collected logic.\nWe must not be swayed by\nour prejudices, played upon\nby 'd&rnagbgues either of the\nleft or the right. This does not\nmean we must descend into\nwhat the realists .call \u2019\u2018prac\ntical thinking.\u201d We must be\npractical but we must use the\nyardstick of our ideals to\n-temper our emotions.\nConfident in our own\nstrength, confident by virtue\nof our experience, that a\nworld, in which no man need\nfear because of his beliefs, his\nfaiths or his ancestry, is the\nsafest world for all, we must,\nwith proper dignity, accept\nthe responsibilities of matur\nity.\nGuam May Seek\nU, S. Workers To\nFinish Harbor\nGUAM\u2014(LPA) War has\nscarred the face of Guam fright\nfully but now with peace it is\nprobable that this 225 square\nmile island will recapture some\nof the pristine beauty that made\nit one of the most magnificently\nscenic spots in the entire Pacific.\nWith the end of hostilities\nhundreds of workers in the U.\nS. may be asked within the next\nyear to come out here to work\n5400 miles from the mainland.\nIf the Navy turns over the job\nof finishing Guam\u2019s huge harbor\nproject to private contractors the\ncivilian workers will be needed\nin many capacities. There is\nsome official sentiment, how\never, for the Navy to do the job\nitself using Seabees, as at pres\nent, on the work.\nII u/l,\nCoiyplynents\nTo,Labar\nNewspaper\nTo!e\nPressmen's Union\nLocal No. 27\nI\nAsk For This Label\nT^bErI)^|JCOUNaL\nToledo Allied\nPrinting Trades\nI Council\nODT Takes Over I. C. In\nFirst Peacetime Seizure\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014Wartime plant seizure powers of the\nPresident got their first peacetime application last week when\nPresident Truman ordered the Office of Defense Transportation\nto take over the Illinois Central railroad, one of the nation's\nlargest carriers.\nReuther\nDemands\n30% Increase\nDETROIT, Mich. Wal\nter P. Reuther, vice-president\nand director of the G-M De\npartment of the UAW-CIO,\ntoday served demands upon\nthe General Motors Corporation\nfor a 30% increase in wages of\nthe 300,000 auto workers cover\ned by the Agreement between\n.the Corporation and the inter\nnational Union.\nIn a letter to C. E. Wilson,\nCorporation President, Reuther\npointed out that President Tru\nman had just announced a new\nwage and price stabilization pol\nicy for the reconversion period.\nUnder this policy, wage increases\nare permissible so long as they\ndo not necessitate increases in\nprices.\nHe said: \u201cWith this policy we\nin the UAW-CIO are hearty ac\ncord. We have maintained all\nalong that the public interest de\nmands effective, stringent price\ncontrol and we in the ranks of\norganized labor are proud of\nthe role we have played in pro\ntecting the consumer interest\nagainst the pressure ol war pro\nfiteers.\u201d\nCites GM Profits\nReuther\u2019s letter cited the tre\nmendous profits, reserves, tax\nrefunds and insurance provisions\nwhich serve to cushion the Cor\nporation against the impact of\nreconversion. He stated: \u201cThe\nprofit and reserve position of\nGM provides ample margin for\nabsorption of this adjustment\nwithout necessitating any price\nincrease.\u201d\nReuther charged that GM pro\nfits before taxes in 1944 were\n78% more than the yearly aver\nage for 1936 to 1939, and that\nthe Corporation\u2019s net worth in\ncreased 22% during the war.\nLabor productivity has increased\nsharply as well, while the Cor\nporation has available to it from\nihe government many millions in\nbash refunds on excess profits\ntaxes and additional refunds in\n(he event that profits fall below\nprewar levels.\nThe demand for a 30% in\ncrease, Reuther said, is neces\nsary to maintain take-home pay,\nwhich has been reduced 30%\nby reduction to a 40-hour week,\nif we are to avoid the threat of\ndrastic deflation. He emphasized\nthat his proposal would neces\nsitate no price increase, due to\nthe swollen profits of the! Cor\nporation.\nHe further proposed that the\nGeneral Corporation take the\ninitiative in calling an industry\nwide conference to negotiate\nsuch an increase on an overall\nindustry-wide basis, so that there\nwould be no problem of jockey\ning for competitive position in\nthis situation. In the event of\nthe calling of such a conference,\nthe demand on GM would be\nwithdrawn in favor of an\ndustry-wide demand by\nUAW-CIO.\nWMC Seeks\nVet-Students\nWASHINGTON (LPA) \u2014The\nWar Manpower Commission\nwants to enroll 12,000 students\nfor medical, dental, pre-medical\nand pre-dental schools from\namong veterans now being dis\ncharged from the armed serv\nices, Chairman Paul V. McNutt\nannounced last week. Financial\nassistance under the GI Bill of\nRights will be high-lighted and\nthe opportunities of these pro\nfessions stressed, in an effort to\nfill the gaps the war caused in\nmedical and dental ranks.\n31B Erie St-\nTruman directed seizure of\nthe road just a short time be\nfore a scheduled strike by the\nBrotherhood of Locomot ive\nFiremen and Enginemen. Im\nmediately thereafter the Broth\nerhood called off the walkout.\nThe unions\nRobertson, explained that\nwill not strike\nernment.\u201d\npresident, D.\nif your Social\nSecurity No.\n\u00a3nd In\n6\n1\n2\n3\n5\n6\n7\n8\n9\nin\nthe\n'we\nagainst\nthe gov-\nwas ac\nCentral\ndispute\nIllinois\nBack of the\nWon by the\nmanagement in altering rules\nin effect for 40 years, governing\nseniority of firemen promoted\nto engineers. The change wac\nmade reputedly at the demand\nof a rival\nBrotherhood\ngineers.\norganization, the\nof Locomotive En-\ncharged the man\nRobertson\nagement revised the rules with\nout consulting his Brothernood\nand that this constituted a vio\nlation of the union\u2019s agreement\nThe controversy, which origi\nnated some months ago, eventu\nally led to a strike vote. An\nEmergency Board, appointed by\nthe President, investigated the\ndispute, but handed down rec\nommendations which were\ncharacterized by the union as\nso \u201cmuddled\u201d that none of the\nparties would accept it.\nAs a result, the Brotherhood\nfixed a strike date. In an effort\nto avert a stoppage, the White\nHouse called the parties to\nWashington for a conference in\nan endeavor to work out a\nsettlement. When that failed\nthe order seizing the road was\nissued.\n1. U. C. TpH How\nTo File Claims\nCOLUMBUS, O., August 28\n\u2014Instructions to unemployed\nworkers on when and how to file\nclaims for unemployment com\npensation were issued today by\nthe Ohio Bureau of Unemploy\nment Compensation as follows:\n1. Do not fHe until at least\none calendar week (Sunday\nthrough Saturday) haff tran\nspired during which you are\ntotally unemployed or your\nweekly earnings are less than\n$16. Meanwhile, register for\nwork. with the United States\nEmployment Service and look\nfor a job.\n2. File your claim during the\nweek following your first calen\ndar week of unemployment, if\nyou are still unemployed. Go to\nthe Local Office of the Bureau\nand USES nearest your resi\ndence on the day of the week\nto be determined by the last\ndigit of your Social Security\ncard number, as follows:\nReport at\nthe Local\nOffice\nMonday\nA. M.\nP. M.\nA. M.\nP. M.\nA. M.\nP. M.\nA. M.\nP. M.\nA. M.\nP. M.\nMonday\n......Tuesday\u2019\n......Tuesday'\nWednesday\nWednesday\n.....Thursday\n....Thursday\n.......Friday\nFriday\n8. After filing your claim, you\nwill be required to register for\nwork\nwork\nyour\nor in\nt\u2019on for which you are reason\nably fitted.\nand you must be able to\nand available for work in\nusual trade or occupation,\nany other trade or occupa-\nFor Specialized\nPrescription Service\nremember it\u2019s\nThe C. R. BUNDT Co,\n314 Mich. AD 5141\n2366 Monroe AD. 6281\nREPAIR NOW!\nLATER WE MIGHT\nZlBE BUSY. CALL\nUS AT GA. 8391\nIt\u2019s real economy tokeep farm buildings and machinery\nIn \u00a3ood repair., better farms will bring victory sooner.\nhech our Farm Machinery Aowl\nUldlit All Aecettaary Ihpairt ,Vom!\nProtect What ou Produced 1\nThe nnnif Ol Chaimen Machin Pry\n1150 W CENTRAL AVE. GA 8391\niEIUhMLVS.Our\nLNC.\nOffice Equipment and Supplier\nUnion U'aterAinrked Paper Specialty\n__________ ____:_______3211MAin\nUSES Takes Lead\nIn Cutting Wages\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014A danger signal that wages\nare being cut on a wholesale basis as reconversion starts\nwas pointed out last week by the CIO.\nAt a special meeting of the executive officers and vice\npresidents of the CIO, a statement was drawn up condemn\ning the \u201cvicious\u201d practice of\nthe United States Employ\nment Service in referring\nL-M Session He'd\nAt White Haute\nWASHINGTON (LPA) Aug.\n27\u2014At a White House confer\nence last week, first steps were\ntaken toward calling the pro\nposed labor-management confer\nence on relations in peacetime.\nAnother meeting of union and\nemployer representatives is now\nscheduled for Sept. 5.\nAt -the White House session\nwere CIO President Philip Mur\nray. AFL President William\nGreen, Eric Johnston, president\nof the United States Chamber of\nCommerce Ira Mosher, presi\ndent of the National Association\nof Manufacturers John W. Sny\nder, director of the Office of\nWar Mobilization and Reconver\nsion, and Labor Secretary Lewis\nSchwellenbach.\nAgreement that careful prep\naration of a conference agenda,\nand inclusion of other labor and\nindustrial groups presumably\nto take in the railroad brother\nhoods and miners\u2014are essential\nto success of the conference, was\nreported by Secretary Schwel\nlenbach.\nAs reported by the CIO, Sec\nretary of Commerce Henry Wal\nlace will be called into future\nplanning sessions to serve as one\nof the government representa\ntives on the body.\nNo agreement on the time of\nthe conference itself, or on the\nscope of the discussion, has yet\nbeen reached, Schwellenbach\nmade clear.\nThe\" proposal for such a con\nference has been made by Presi\ndent Truman, who believes that\nlabor-management peace is es\nsential to successful transition\nfrom a war economy to a peace\ntime one.\nStill lying dormant is the La\nbor-Industry Peace Charter\ndrawn up last spring by repre\nsentatives of the C. of C., AFL\nand CIO. The NAM never went\nalong in this statement of the\nrequisites for industrial peace,\nand this fact is expected to be a\nstumbling block to reaching any\nagreements this time.\nPage Seven\nskilled workers who ire unem\nployed to jobs at drastically\nlower wages than they have\nbeen receiving heretofore. This\ndone, according to reports\nfrom local unions, even though\nthe new job iff one that does the\nskills of the unemployed work\ner.\nThe CIO called on the USES\nto refuse to refer men to jobs\nat lower wages than they had\npreviously received or to jobs\nthat will not utilize skills in\nfull.. They urged State CIO\ncouncils to \u201cbring this matter\nforceably to the attention of\nthe Unemployment Compensa\ntion Divisions in their respective\nstates and demand the disconti\nnuance of this practice where it\nis now in vogue and to take all\nsteps necessary to protect the\nunemployed workers in their\nclaims for unemployment com\npensation.\u201d\nItalian Workers Strike\nA general strike of state em\nployes in Northern Italy began\non August 10. Railroad workers\nand other workers in essential\npublic services are not partici\npating. The cause of the stride\nis the refusal on the part of the\nAllied authorities to meet in full\nthe demands of the state em\nployes. The Allied authorities\nhad decided to put into effect\nmeasures for the equalization of\nwages between the North and\nthe South on August 1, but the\nstate employes claim that they\nshould be retroactive to. May\n1st.\ntMm7! 1 POTATO\nCHIPS\nA\nSee BASCH\u2019S for GLASSES!\nDefense workers! Protect your vision\nnd improve your eyesight with\nproper glasses. Al? preseriptrons a\ncuraLeli fiilejL Satisfaction guaxai*\n1\nOne of Oncle'Sam\u2019s\n\"7 Bsslc fooas\"\n^CREDIT\n^COMPLETE WITH\nIs milk We are proud that\nSealfest K^iik is on of\nthe finest in America.\nLEWSES A\u00bb0 FUAMEi\nBASCH\u2019S \u00b0^:u\n-1. I' 1 1\nOhio Clover Leaf\nOhio Clover Leaf\nD\u2019Viston of National Dairy Product* Corp.\nUon'f mist Joan Davis in the SeaHest Village\nStore Program Thursdays 9:3G WSPD","height":"26892","width":"20244"}}
